"\n## Problems\nLet $x$, $y$ and $z$ all exceed $1$ and let $w$ be a positive number such that $\\log_x w = 24$, $\\log_y w = 40$ and $\\log_{xyz} w = 12$. Find $\\log_z w$. Show that it is 060.\n\n## Informal proof\nThe [[logarithm]]ic notation doesn't tell us much, so we'll first convert everything to the equivalent exponential forms.\n\n$x^{24}=w$, $y^{40}=w$, and $(xyz)^{12}=w$. If we now convert everything to a power of $120$, it will be easy to isolate $z$ and $w$.\n\n$x^{120}=w^5$, $y^{120}=w^3$, and $(xyz)^{120}=w^{10}$.\n\nWith some substitution, we get $w^5w^3z^{120}=w^{10}$ and $\\log_zw=060$.\n\n## Formal statement\n```isabelle\ntheorem aime_1983_p1:\n  fixes x y z w :: nat\n  assumes ht : \"1 < x \\<and> 1 < y \\<and> 1 < z\"\n    and hw : \"0 \\<le> w\"\n    and h0 : \"ln w / ln x = 24\"\n    and h1 : \"ln w / ln y = 40\"\n    and h2 : \"ln w / ln (x * y * z) = 12\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln z = 60\"\n```\n\n## Structured informal proof\nStep 1: Convert the logarithmic equations to exponential form.\nStep 2: Raise each equation to the power of 5 to make the exponents of $w$ multiples of 5.\nStep 3: Substitute the expressions for $x^{120}$ and $y^{120}$ into the equation for $(xyz)^{120}$.\nStep 4: Simplify the equation to isolate $z^{120}$.\nStep 5: Convert the equation back to logarithmic form to find $\\log_z w$.\n\n## Lemmas\n### Lemma 1\nA lemma showing that $\\log_b a = c$ is equivalent to $b^c = a$ would be useful for converting between logarithmic and exponential forms.\n\n### Code 1\n```isabelle\nlemma log_exp_equiv:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"b \u2260 1\"\n  shows \"log b a = c \u27f7 b^c = a\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 2\nA lemma showing that $(ab)^c = a^c b^c$ would be useful for simplifying the equation in Step 3.\n\n### Code 2\n```isabelle\nlemma exp_mult:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\"\n  shows \"(a * b)^c = a^c * b^c\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 3\nA lemma showing that $\\log_b a^c = c \\log_b a$ would be useful for converting the equation back to logarithmic form in Step 5.\n\n### Code 3\n```isabelle\nlemma log_exp_mult:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"b \u2260 1\"\n  shows \"log b (a^c) = c * log b a\"\n```\n\nThese lemmas provide the necessary tools to convert between logarithmic and exponential forms, simplify the equation, and convert it back to logarithmic form to find the desired value."